### Visibility Modifiers in Kotlin

Visibility modifiers control access to classes, objects, interfaces, constructors, functions, properties, and their setters.

---

### The Four Modifiers

| Modifier | Visibility |
|----------|------------|
| `public` (default) | Visible everywhere |
| `internal` | Visible within the same module |
| `protected` | Visible in the class and subclasses |
| `private` | Visible within the file or class |

---

### Top-Level Visibility

At the file level (top-level declarations):

```kotlin
public val publicVal = "Visible everywhere"
internal val internalVal = "Visible in module"
private val privateVal = "Visible in this file"
// protected not allowed at top level
```

---

### Class Member Visibility

```kotlin
open class MyClass {
    public val a = "Public"     // Visible everywhere
    internal val b = "Internal"  // Visible in module
    protected val c = "Protected"  // Visible in class and subclasses
    private val d = "Private"     // Visible only in this class

    fun test() {
        println(a)  // OK
        println(b)  // OK
        println(c)  // OK
        println(d)  // OK
    }
}

class SubClass : MyClass() {
    fun test() {
        println(a)  // OK
        println(b)  // OK
        println(c)  // OK (protected accessible)
        // println(d)  // Error: Private
    }
}
```

---

### Constructor Visibility

Make constructors private to control instantiation.

```kotlin
class Singleton private constructor() {
    companion object {
        val instance: Singleton by lazy { Singleton() }
    }
}
```

---

### Setter Visibility

```kotlin
class Person {
    var name: String = ""
        private set  // Can read publicly, set only internally

    fun updateName(newName: String) {
        name = newName  // OK from within the class
    }
}

fun main() {
    val p = Person()
    // p.name = "Alice"  // Error: Setter is private
    println(p.name)  // OK: Getter is public
}
```

---

### Module Scope

`internal` visibility means accessible within the same module (a set of Kotlin files compiled together).

```kotlin
// File in module A
internal class InternalClass

// File in module B -- cannot access InternalClass
```

> **Key Point:** The default visibility in Kotlin is `public`, not `private` (unlike some languages). Use `internal` for module-internal APIs.

codeExample:
open class Vehicle {
    public val brand = "Generic"
    internal val engineCode = "V8"
    protected val vin = "ABC123"
    private val secret = "hidden"

    fun getInfo(): String {
        return "$brand $vin $secret"  // All accessible here
    }
}

class Car : Vehicle() {
    fun carInfo(): String {
        return "$brand - $engineCode - $vin"  // secret not accessible
    }
}

fun main() {
    val car = Car()
    println(car.brand)      // OK
    // println(car.vin)     // Error: protected
    // println(car.secret)  // Error: private
    println(car.getInfo())
}
